{{Paleolithic|upper}}
'''Emiran culture''' was a culture that existed in the [[Levant]] ([[Syria]], [[Lebanon]], [[Israel]], [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]]) between the [[Middle Paleolithic]] and the [[Upper Paleolithic]] periods.
Emiran culture apparently developed from the local [[Mousterian]] without rupture, keeping numerous elements of the Levalloise-Mousterian, together with the locally typical [[Emireh point]]. The Emireh point is the type tool of stage one of the [[Upper Paleolithic]], first identified in the Emiran culture.<ref name="CopelandWescombe1965">{{cite book|author1=Lorraine Copeland|author2=P. Wescombe|title=Inventory of Stone-Age sites in Lebanon, p. 48 & Figure IV, 4, p. 150|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6YsRRwAACAAJ|accessdate=21 July 2011|year=1965|publisher=Imprimerie Catholique}}</ref> Numerous stone blade tools were used, including curved knives similar to those found in the [[Chatelperronian]] culture of Western Europe.
The Emiran eventually evolved into the [[Antelian]] culture, still of Levalloise tradition but with some [[Aurignacian]] influences.
According to [[Dorothy Garrod]], the Emireh point, known from several sites in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], is the hallmark of this culture.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=vROM3JrrRa0C&pg=PA54&lpg=PA54&dq=emireh+point+israel&source=bl&ots=KwCNSnaJb6&sig=8QNCT80dYEbXlgEumNarGonX02o&hl=en&sa=X&ei=_7RBUbD0GLLY4QTXg4DABQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=emireh%20point%20israel&f=true Archaeology in Cultural Systems, Sally R. Binford, Lewish Roberts Binford]</ref>
